      <p><strong>1. Drainage Problems:</strong></p>
      <p>Drainage issues are a frequent problem in commercial washers and can significantly disrupt operations. Common
        symptoms include water failing to drain properly from the drum, leading to standing water and potential overflow. This
        can be caused by blockages in the drain pump or hoses, or a malfunctioning drain pump motor. Debris such as lint,
        coins, or fabric can clog the drainage system, impeding water flow. Regular maintenance can help prevent these issues,
        but once they occur, addressing them promptly is crucial. Repair costs for drainage problems typically range from $100
        to $300, depending on the severity of the blockage and whether parts need to be replaced.</p>
      <p><strong>2. Spin Cycle Issues:</strong></p>
      <p>Problems with the spin cycle can leave clothes soaking wet, making them difficult to dry and delaying laundry
        operations. These issues can stem from a variety of sources, including a malfunctioning lid switch, a worn-out drive
        belt, or an imbalanced load. Additionally, problems with the washer's motor or electronic control board can prevent
        the spin cycle from engaging properly. Diagnosing and repairing spin cycle issues often requires a skilled technician,
        with costs ranging from $150 to $400, depending on the specific cause and the parts required.</p>
      <p><strong>3. Water Inlet Problems:</strong></p>
      <p>Water inlet issues can prevent a commercial washer from filling correctly, either resulting in no water or
        insufficient water levels to wash clothes effectively. Common causes include faulty water inlet valves, clogged inlet
        screens, or issues with the washerâ€™s electronic control board. Regular inspection and cleaning of inlet screens can
        help mitigate these problems. When they do occur, repairs typically involve replacing the water inlet valve or
        addressing electronic issues, with costs ranging from $100 to $300.</p>
      <p><strong>4. Door Lock Malfunctions:</strong></p>
      <p>For front-load washers, door lock malfunctions are a common issue that can prevent the machine from starting or
        completing a cycle. This can be due to a faulty door latch, problems with the door lock switch, or issues with the
        control board. In some cases, the door might not close properly due to physical damage or wear and tear. Repairing or
        replacing the door lock mechanism can cost between $150 and $350, depending on the complexity of the issue and the
        specific parts needed.</p>
      <p><strong>5. Excessive Noise and Vibration:</strong></p>
      <p>Excessive noise and vibration are often indicative of underlying problems in a commercial washer. Common causes
        include worn-out drum bearings, unbalanced loads, or issues with the suspension system that supports the drum. These
        issues can lead to louder-than-normal operation and significant vibration, especially during the spin cycle.
        Addressing these problems usually involves replacing worn parts and ensuring the machine is properly leveled. Repair
        costs can vary widely, typically ranging from $200 to $600, depending on the specific issue and the parts involved.
      </p>
      <p><strong>6. Electronic Control Board Failures:</strong></p>
      <p>The electronic control board is the brain of a commercial washer, governing all its functions. When this component
        fails, it can lead to a wide range of issues, from the washer not starting to cycles not completing properly. Control
        board failures can be caused by power surges, moisture ingress, or simply wear and tear over time. Diagnosing and
        replacing an electronic control board is often a complex and costly repair, with expenses ranging from $300 to $800,
        depending on the washer model and the availability of replacement parts.</p>
      <p><strong>7. Leaking Water:</strong></p>
      <p>Water leaks can occur for several reasons, including damaged door seals, worn-out hoses, or issues with the water
        pump. Leaks not only waste water but can also cause damage to surrounding areas and pose a safety hazard. Identifying
        the source of the leak is crucial, and repairs can involve replacing seals, hoses, or the pump itself. Repair costs
        for water leaks typically range from $150 to $400, depending on the severity and location of the leak. Regular
        inspection and maintenance can help prevent leaks and ensure the longevity of the washer.</p>
